- VSCode Version: 1.8.0-insider
- OS Version: OSX 10.11.6 (15G1108)

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create an extension.
2. Implement a command like this:
```
// package.json
{
    // ...
    "contributes": {
        "commands": [
            {
                "command": "customDelete",
                "title": "Custom Delete"
            }
        ]
    }    
    // ...
}
```
```ts
// extension.ts
import {commands, window, ExtensionContext} from 'vscode';

export function activate(context: ExtensionContext) {
    commands.registerCommand('customDelete', () => {
        const activeTextEditor = window.activeTextEditor;

        activeTextEditor.edit(editBuilder => {
            activeTextEditor.selections.forEach(selection => {
               editBuilder.delete(selection);
            });
        });
    });
}
```
3. Debug the extension.
4. Enter some text:
```
foofoofoo, foofoofoo, bar
```
5. Select those two `foofoofoo` using `cmd+d`.
6. Run the implemented command.
7. Selections are broken.

Screen record:
![2016-11-09 18 55 43](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2175401/20134274/34c68862-a6ae-11e6-8f81-bad3a74d4d82.gif)

- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version: Windows 10

The following does not highlight correctly:
```
.test {
    &--foo { color: white; }
    &#{&}--bar { color: black; }
    &some-#{$placeholder} { color: green; }
}
```

![example](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/138147/20122361/f9eaab70-a5cb-11e6-9ecf-a660384d33b4.png)

Expected would be for the entire selector to remain green, and if possible, have the interpolation highlighted individually.

I've tested with all bundled themes, and they are all wrong in slightly different ways, so I assume the problem lies with the language provider.
